## Claim
By redefining the potential function to $\Phi_{\mathcal{O}}'(u,v)= \Phi_{\mathcal{O}} - c_1 L_n(u,v)$, where $L_n(u,v) = 2r_n \cos(\beta - \gamma)$ and $c_1 \approx 0.0308$, the target function $\Upsilon_{\mathcal{O}}(u,v)$ remainsstrictly negative for a stretch factor $\rho = 1.98$. This modification effectively compensates for the derivative slack in the pivotalpoint analysis (Proposition 7), allowing for a tighter global bound.

## Derivation

### 1. Redefinition ofthe Potential Function
We define the modified potential function $\Phi_{\mathcal{O}}'$ as:
\begin{equation}
\Phi_{\mathcal{O}}'(u,v) = \varphi(r_n - r_1)- \frac{\varphi}{3} \sum_{i=2}^{n} (2H_i + V_i) - c_1 L_n(u,v)
\end{equation}
where $L_n(u,v)$ is the length of the chord formed by the intersection of the line $uv$ andthe disk $O_n$. For an unobstructed pair $(u,v)$, $L_n(u,v) =2r_n \cos(\beta - \gamma)$. 

The target function becomes:
\begin{equation}
\Upsilon_{\mathcal{O}}(u,v) = |P_{\mathcal{O}}(u,v)| - \lambda |D_{\mathcal{O}}(u,v)| + \Phi_{\mathcal{O}} -c_1 L_n(u,v)
\end{equation}

### 2. Differential Analysisof the Chord Term
To satisfy Proposition 7, we require $\frac{\partial \Upsilon_{\mathcal{O}}}{\partial X_{o_n}} \leq 0$. We compute the partial derivative of $L_n$ with respect to thex-coordinate of the center $o_n$:
Using $L_n = 2r_n \cos(\beta - \gamma)$, we have:
\begin{align*}
\frac{\partial L_n}{\partial X_{o_n}} &= 2 \frac{\partial r_n}{\partial X_{o_n}} \cos(\beta - \gamma) - 2r_n \sin(\beta - \gamma) \left( \frac{\partial \beta}{\partial X_{o_n}} - \frac{\partial \gamma}{\partial X_{o_n}} \right) \\
&= -2 \cos \alpha \cos(\beta - \gamma)- 2r_n \sin(\beta - \gamma) \left( \frac{\beta \cos \alpha}{r_n} - \frac{\partial \gamma}{\partial X_{o_n}} \right)\\
&= -2 \cos \alpha (\cos(\beta - \gamma) + \beta \sin(\beta - \gamma)) + 2r_n \sin(\beta - \gamma) \frac{\partial \gamma}{\partialX_{o_n}}
\end{align*}
where $\frac{\partial \gamma}{\partial X_{o_n}}$ is the angular shift of the ray $uv$ required to maintain $v$ as a pivotal point.### 3. Impact on the Nuclear Function $g_i(\alpha)$
